SIMPLE: peck
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Peck
<hw>Peck</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Perh. akin to <ets>pack</ets>; or,
orig., an indefinite quantity, and fr. <ets>peck</ets>, v. (below): cf.
also F. <ets>picotin</ets> a peak.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The fourth
part of a bushel; a dry measure of eight quarts; <as>as, a <ex>peck</ex>
of wheat</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧A <xex>peck</xex> of provender.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A great deal; a large or excessive quantity.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧A <xex>peck</xex> of uncertainties and doubts.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Milton.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>
` <p><ent>Peck</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Peck
<hw>Peck</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Pecked</conjf> <pr>(p⟦ecr⟧kt)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Pecking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[See <er>Pick</er>,
<pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To strike with the beak; to thrust
the beak into; <as>as, a bird <ex>pecks</ex> a tree</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence: To strike, pick, thrust against, or dig into,
with a pointed instrument; especially, to strike, pick, etc., with
repeated quick movements.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To seize and pick up with the beak, or as with the
beak; to bite; to eat; -- often with <xex>up</xex>.</def>
<rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This fellow <qex>pecks</qex> up wit as pigeons peas.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To make, by striking with the beak or a pointed
instrument; <as>as, to <ex>peck</ex> a hole in a tree</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Peck</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Peck
<hw>Peck</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make strokes with
the beak, or with a pointed instrument.</def>
<rj><au>Carew.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To pick up food with the beak; hence, to
eat.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[The hen] went <qex>pecking</qex> by his side.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To peck at</b></col>, <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>to attack with
petty and repeated blows; to carp at; to nag; to tease.</cd>
<sd>(a)</sd> <cd>to eat slowly and in small portions, with litle
interest; <as>as, to <ex>peck at</ex> one's food</as>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1056 --></p>

<p><ent>Peck</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Peck
<hw>Peck</hw> <pr>(p⟦ecr⟧k)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A quick, sharp
stroke, as with the beak of a bird or a pointed instrument.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pecker</ent>⟦br⟧
